welcome_screens.title: Investigating the factors leading to dog bites to children

properties.description:
This survey is for parents/guardians who had children and dog(s) in the home at the same time. 

The purpose of this study is to support a national dog bite prevention program. The answers to this survey will support us enormously in helping families stay safe and together. Results will be distributed once the analysis is complete.

Thank you.

_Disclaimer and trigger warning: _
_Some questions ask for details surrounding dog bites to children._

fields.title: Have any of your children ever been bitten by one or more of your dog(s)?
The next questions should be answered for one child's experience. Please give the child's first name or initial

properties.description: If more than one of your children have been bitten by a dog, start with the oldest.  You'll be able to submit answers for other children by retaking this survey at the end.

fields.title: Answer the following questions about the first time this child was bitten by your dog. You will be able to submit answers again for additional incidents.
How old was {{field:6957a284-41a8-43d8-985b-604401786234}} at the time of the bite?

properties.description: Please use whole numbers, unless the child was under 1 year then denote how many months old, for example, 6 m.

properties.description: Choose any that apply

choices.label: Whale Eye (whites of the dog's eyes are showing, like a slide-eye look)

fields.title: Describe what happened to trigger the biting incident. Did it occur when {{field:6957a284-41a8-43d8-985b-604401786234}}:

choices.label: Pet the dog on the head
Pet the dog on its legs or paws
Gave the dog a belly rub
Approached the dog while it had a toy
Approached the dog while it was eating or near its food bowl
Approached the dog while it was chewing a bone, rawhide, or treat
Approached the dog while it was on it's bed, in it's crate, or sleeping
Stepped or fell on the dog
Tried to stop the dog from doing something (restraining the dog)
Put on or take off its collar

fields.title: Was the dog leashed or tethered when the bite occurred?
What was the severity of the bite?

properties.description:
Use the image for reference
_Designed by Vivian Zottola, MSc; Illustrated by Milena Salieri._

choices.label: Score 1 - Low Forewarning: No physical contact
Score 2 - Moderate Forewarning: Teeth made contact with skin but no visible injury. Bruising, but teeth did not penetrate skin.
Score 3 - Serious Forewarning: Bit and penetrated skin leaving puncture wounds, stitches not needed.
Score 4 - Very Serious Contact: Severe bite with tearing of the skin. Medical attention and/or stitches required.
